07685nam a22010815i 9783110631135DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019931984  a97831106311357 a10.1515/97831106311352doi  a(DE-B1597)506708  a(OCoLC)1102794682  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPN56.C663bN37 2019 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.93355622300aNarratives of Annihilation, Confinement, and Survival :bCamp Literature in a Transnational Perspective /ced. by Anja Tippner, Anna Artwińska. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (VI, 280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture & Conflict ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Camp Narratives in a Comparative Transnational Perspective -- tI: Comparing Camp Narratives: Theoretical Approaches -- tTowards a Literary History of Concentration Camps: Comparative or “Entangled”? -- tWorlds Apart? Cross-mapping Camp Literature from the Gulag and Nazi Concentration Camps -- tII: Defining Camp Literatures: Overview -- tTranscultural Memorial Forms in Post-Soviet Estonian Narratives of the Gulag -- tRepresentations of the Gulag and Methods of Resistance: Romanian Detention Memoirs -- tPolish Literature of Soviet Prison Camps: An Outline of Issues -- tBetween the Sun and the Stone – The Naked Body: Yugoslav “Re-education” Camps in Literary Representations -- tPresence through Absence: The Aesthetics of Blank Space in French Holocaust Literature and Film -- tKonzentrationslager in Polish Literature: From Metaphorization to Metaphor -- tIII: Witnessing and Remembering Camp Experiences: Comparative Case Studies -- tThe Grey Zones of Witnessing: Levi, Améry, Shalamov -- tThe Ghetto of Leningrad, the Siege of Theresienstadt: A Comparative Reading of Enforced Communities -- tUncanny Contingencies: Translation, Comparison, and Compassion in Herta Müller’s The Hunger Angel -- tA Communist Woman in the Gulag: Gender, Ideology, and Limit-Experience in Ginzburg and Budzyńska -- tTrauma Narration as Adventure Fiction: Ivan Bahrianyj’s Novel The Hunters and the Hunted -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Topics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of “camp narratives” rather than “Holocaust narratives” or “Gulag narratives” is based on the assumption that literary accounts of camp experiences share common traits, aesthetically as well as thematically. The book presents readings of camp literature that underscore the similarities between texts about Soviet gulag camps, Nazi camps and about other camp experiences. While literature about Nazi concentration camps still serves as a point of reference for camp narratives in the same way that the Holocaust serves as a point of reference for other genocidal operations, socialist labor and penal camps have become transnational lieux de mémoire in their own right since 1989. This volume intends to provide a theoretical frame as well as an overview of several important European camp literatures and case studies of iconic camp narratives and to take a comparative and transnational perspective on the genre of the camp narrative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aConcentration camp inmates' writingsxHistory and criticism. 0aHolocaust survivors' writingsxHistory and criticism. 0aInternment camps in literature. 0aLiterature and transnationalism. 0aPolitical prisoners' writingsxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aCamp narratives.  aGulag literature.  aHolocaust literature.  aculture of remembrance.1 aArtwińska, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArtwińska, Anna, e